							<div class=3D"mw-indicators">
		</div>

						<div id=3D"siteSub" class=3D"noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encycl=
opedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div role=3D"note" c=
lass=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">This article is about sets thems=
elves. For the branches of mathematics studying sets, see <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_set_theory" title=3D"Naive set theory">Naive =
set theory</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory" tit=
le=3D"Set theory">Set theory</a>. For the category of sets, see <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_(category_theory)" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Set (category theory)">Set (category theory)</a>.</div>
<div class=3D"shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=
=3D"display:none">Collection of mathematical objects</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Example_of_a_set.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descri=
ption"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3=
7/Example_of_a_set.svg/250px-Example_of_a_set.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" w=
idth=3D"250" height=3D"222" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"45=
0" data-file-height=3D"400"></a><figcaption>A set of polygons in an <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler_diagram" title=3D"Euler diagram">Eu=
ler diagram</a></figcaption></figure>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Example_of_a_set_rearranged.svg" class=3D"mw-=
file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/common=
s/thumb/0/05/Example_of_a_set_rearranged.svg/250px-Example_of_a_set_rearran=
ged.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"222" class=3D"mw-fi=
le-element" data-file-width=3D"450" data-file-height=3D"400"></a><figcaptio=
n>This set equals the one above since they have the same elements.</figcapt=
ion></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, a <b>set</b> is a collection of different things; t=
he things are <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Element_(mathemat=
ics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Element (mathematics)">elements</a></i=
> or <i>members</i> of the set and are typically <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_object" title=3D"Mathematical object">mathemati=
cal objects</a>: numbers, symbols, points in space, lines, other <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_shape" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Geometric shape">geometric shapes</a>, variables, or other sets.  A set=
 may be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finite_set" title=3D"Finit=
e set">finite</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinite_set"=
 title=3D"Infinite set">infinite</a>. There is a unique set with no element=
s, called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empty_set" title=3D"=
Empty set">empty set</a>; a set with a single element is a <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Singleton_(mathematics)" title=3D"Singleton (mathe=
matics)">singleton</a>. =20
</p><p>Sets are ubiquitous in modern mathematics. Indeed, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory" title=3D"Set theory">set theory</a>, mo=
re specifically <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zermelo%E2%80%93Fr=
aenkel_set_theory" title=3D"Zermelo=E2=80=93Fraenkel set theory">Zermelo=E2=
=80=93Fraenkel set theory</a>, has been the standard way to provide rigorou=
s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foundations_of_mathematics" titl=
e=3D"Foundations of mathematics">foundations</a> for all branches of mathem=
atics since the first half of the 20th century.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Context">Context</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSet_(mathematics)&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Context"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Before the end of the 19th century, sets were not studied specifically, =
and were not clearly distinguished from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Sequence_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sequence (math=
ematics)">sequences</a>. Most mathematicians considered <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinity_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Infinity (mathematics)">infinity</a> as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Potential_infinity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Potential infi=
nity">potential</a>=E2=80=94meaning that it is the result of an endless pro=
cess=E2=80=94and were reluctant to consider <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Infinite_set" title=3D"Infinite set">infinite sets</a>, that is s=
ets whose number of members is not a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Natural_number" title=3D"Natural number">natural number</a>. Specificall=
y, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_(geometry)" title=3D"Lin=
e (geometry)">line</a> was not considered as the set of its points, but as =
a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Locus_(mathematics)" title=3D"Lo=
cus (mathematics)">locus</a> where points may be located.=20
</p><p>The mathematical study of infinite sets began with <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georg_Cantor" title=3D"Georg Cantor">Georg Cantor</=
a> (1845=E2=80=931918). This provided some counterintuitive facts and parad=
oxes. For example, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_line=
" title=3D"Number line">number line</a> has an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Cardinal_number" title=3D"Cardinal number">infinite number</a>=
 of elements that is strictly larger than the infinite number of <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_number" title=3D"Natural number">nat=
ural numbers</a>, and any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Line_seg=
ment" title=3D"Line segment">line segment</a> has the same number of elemen=
ts as the whole space. Also, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russe=
ll%27s_paradox" title=3D"Russell's paradox">Russell's paradox</a> implies t=
hat the phrase "the set of all sets" is self-contradictory.
</p><p>Together with other counterintuitive results, this led to the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foundational_crisis_of_mathematics" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Foundational crisis of mathematics">foundational=
 crisis of mathematics</a>, which was eventually resolved with the general =
adoption of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zermelo%E2%80%93Fraenk=
el_set_theory" title=3D"Zermelo=E2=80=93Fraenkel set theory">Zermelo=E2=80=
=93Fraenkel set theory</a> as a robust foundation of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory" title=3D"Set theory">set theory</a> and all =
mathematics.=20
</p><p>Meanwhile, sets started to be widely used in all mathematics. In par=
ticular, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_structure" titl=
e=3D"Algebraic structure">algebraic structures</a> and <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_space" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Mat=
hematical space">mathematical spaces</a> are typically defined in terms of =
sets. Also, many older mathematical results are restated in terms of sets. =
For example, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_theorem" t=
itle=3D"Euclid's theorem">Euclid's theorem</a> is often stated as "the <i>s=
et</i> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number" title=
=3D"Prime number">prime numbers</a> is infinite". This wide use of sets in =
mathematics was prophesied by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Davi=
d_Hilbert" title=3D"David Hilbert">David Hilbert</a> when saying: "No one w=
ill drive us from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cantor%27s_p=
aradise" title=3D"Cantor's paradise">paradise which Cantor created for us</=
a>."<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Set_(mathematics)#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Generally, the common usage of sets in mathematics does not require =
the full power of Zermelo=E2=80=93Fraenkel set theory. In mathematical prac=
tice, sets can be manipulated independently of the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_logic" title=3D"Mathematical logic">logical f=
ramework</a> of this theory.
</p><p>The object of this article is to summarize the manipulation rules an=
d properties of sets that are commonly used in mathematics, without referen=
ce to any logical framework. For the branch of mathematics that studies set=
s, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_theory" title=3D"Set th=
eory">Set theory</a>; for an informal presentation of the corresponding log=
ical framework, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naive_set_theo=
ry" title=3D"Naive set theory">Naive set theory</a>; for a more formal pres=
entation, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axiomatic_set_theory=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Axiomatic set theory">Axiomatic set theory=
</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zermelo%E2%80%93Fraenkel_=
set_theory" title=3D"Zermelo=E2=80=93Fraenkel set theory">Zermelo=E2=80=93F=
raenkel set theory</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Basic_notions">Basic notion=
s</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSet_(mathe=
matics)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Basic not=
ions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<p>In mathematics, a set is a collection of different things.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-Cantor_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Set_(mathematics)#cite_note-Cantor-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Jai=
nAhmad1995_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Set_(mathematics)#cite_note-JainAhmad1995-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-Goldberg1986_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Set_(mathematics)#cite_note-Goldberg1986-4"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-CormenCormen2001_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Set_(mathematics)#cite_note-CormenCormen2001-5"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The=
se things are called <i>elements</i> or <i>members</i> of the set and are t=
ypically <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_object" titl=
e=3D"Mathematical object">mathematical objects</a> of any kind such as numb=
ers, symbols, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Point_(geometry)" ti=
tle=3D"Point (geometry)">points in space</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Line_(geometry)" title=3D"Line (geometry)">lines</a>, other <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shape" title=3D"Shape">geometrical sh=
apes</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variable_(mathematics)" =
title=3D"Variable (mathematics)">variables</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Function_(mathematics)" title=3D"Function (mathematics)">func=
tions</a>, or even other sets.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHalmos1960[httpsa=
rchiveorgdetailsnaivesettheory00halmpagen11mode2up_1]_6-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_(mathematics)#cite_note-FO=
OTNOTEHalmos1960[httpsarchiveorgdetailsnaivesettheory00halmpagen11mode2up_1=
]-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_(mathematics)#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A set may=
 also be called a <i>collection</i> or family, especially when its elements=
 are themselves sets; this may avoid the confusion between the set and its =
members, and may make reading easier. A set may be specified either by list=
ing its elements or by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Property_=
(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Property (mathematics)">prope=
rty</a> that characterizes its elements, such as for the set of the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_number" title=3D"Prime number">prim=
e numbers</a> or the set of all students in a given class.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-:0_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set=
_(mathematics)#cite_note-:0-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_(mathematics)#cite_no=
te-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_(mathematics)#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>If <span class=3D"nowrap">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"mwe-math-element m=
we-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-math=
ml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Mat=
