<p>There are several standard <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oper=
ation_(mathematics)" title=3D"Operation (mathematics)">operations</a> that =
produce new sets from  given sets, in the same way as <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Addition" title=3D"Addition">addition</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplication" title=3D"Multiplication">=
multiplication</a> produce new numbers from given numbers. The operations t=
hat are considered in this section are those such that all elements of the =
produced sets belong to a previously defined set. These operations are comm=
only illustrated with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler_diagra=
m" title=3D"Euler diagram">Euler diagrams</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Venn_diagram" title=3D"Venn diagram">Venn diagrams</a>.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Set_(mathematics)#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The main basic operations on sets are the following ones.
</p>
