acket">]</span></a></sup> A set with the cardinality of a natural number is=
 called a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finite_set" title=3D"Fin=
ite set">finite set</a> which is true for both cases. Otherwise, one has an=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinite_set" title=3D"Infinite s=
et">infinite set</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_(mathematics)#cite_note-42"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The fact that natural numbers measure the cardinality of finite sets=
 is the basis of the concept of natural number, and predates for several th=
ousands years the concept of sets. A large part of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Combinatorics" title=3D"Combinatorics">combinatorics</a> i=
s devoted to the computation or estimation of the cardinality of finite set=
s.=20
</p>
